<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-117-446  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 117 446.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 5 1990 v7 n5 p31(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Net-management expenditures to rise at Fortune 1000 firms. (marketsurvey)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>A survey of Fortune 1000 companies using multivendor computersystems indicates that most users plan to greatly increasenetwork-management expenditures in 1990 and 1991.andP;  Seventy-fivepercent of respondents say they plan to increase spending by anaverage of 48 percent.andP;  Factors motivating network-systemsintegration include the desire to improve network performance andreliability and to lower personnel costs.andP;  IBM's mainframe-basedNetView is the system most widely considered for purchase, with 55percent of respondents saying they are evaluating it.andP;  Otherpopular architectures include ATandamp;T's Unified Network ManagementArchitecture, DEC's Enterprise Management Architecture, and CincomSystems Inc's Net/Master.andP;  Users cite compatibility with existingsystems and vendor support as important considerations inselecting a network system.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Business PlanningNetwork ManagementSystem SelectionMarket AnalysisSurveyMultivendor Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   IBM tops buyers' network management plans. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paula MusichandM;Multivendor computer-system users in Fortune 1000 companies plan to greatlyincrease spending for integrated network-management systems over the next twoyears, according to a recently released study.andM;Seventy-five percent of respondents from companies in the finance,manufacturing and transportation/utilities industries said they expect toincrease their network-management expenditures by an average of 48 percentover the next two years, according to officials at Business Research Group,which conducted the study titled &quot;User Trends in Integrated NetworkManagement.&quot;andM;&quot;We're seeing an increase [in spending] because users' cumulative investmentin networking technology has reached the point where there is a dramatic needto manage those resources more effectively,&quot; said Kevin O'Neill, vicepresident of network research for the Newton, Mass., firm.andM;Corporations expect to achieve better network performance, greaterreliability and lower personnel costs by implementing integratednetwork-management systems, the study found.andM;&quot;That told us people are still trying to put together their overallinfrastructure, that they're not satisfied with [network] performance, andthat in implementing these systems, they don't want their operating costs torun away from them,&quot; O'Neill said.andM;Only now are integrated network-management systems coming into their own, asmajor computer and network vendors release components that fulfill theircustomers' requirements for multivendor network management, O'Neill said.andM;IBM NetView on TopandM;Of the major systems being considered for purchase, IBM's NetView garneredthe most interest, with 55 percent of respondents looking at themainframe-based system.andM;ATandamp;T's Unified Network Management Architecture claimed a strong second, with37 percent of the respondents considering this approach.andM;Digital Equipment Corp.'s Enterprise Management Architecture and CincomSystems Inc.'s Net/Master took third and fourth places, with 21 percent and20 percent, respectively.andM;Compatibility with existing network-management systems was important tousers, although the vendor's credibility and provision of technicalassistance were rated even higher, the study found.andM;&quot;Users don't want to disrupt their existing business applications,&quot; saidO'Neill.andP;  &quot;They want to add this capability to their existing environments ina graceful way.andM;&quot;Customers are looking for a lot of support from their vendors inimplementing these systems,&quot; he added.andM;The study, based on research gathered from 300 users, is available now.andP;  Itis priced at $9,000.andM;Business Research Group can be contacted at (617) 964-6204.andO;</TEXT></DOC>